  <h3 style=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>3. Saving Money on Food</stro=
ng></h3><h4 style=3D"margin-left:40px;white-space:pre-wrap;">Get a Kitchen =
(or Free Breakfast)</h4><p class=3D"" style=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;">Sampl=
ing local cuisine is a highlight of any trip, but high dining every meal wi=
ll strain a budget.&nbsp; Staying in an apartment or a place that offers ki=
tchen access is where accommodation and food budgets can help each other ou=
t. During our travels, my husband and I like to eat out, on average, once p=
er day. Our daily plans help determine if it is lunch or dinner, with lunch=
 being usually less expensive.&nbsp;<br><br>Cooking your own meals while tr=
avelling creates a healthy balance financially and nutritionally! We eat lo=
cal by shopping at markets or grocery stores - which is an experience in it=
self! Some of our favourite simple meals are very affordable, fresh and loc=
ally inspired including:</p><ul data-rte-list=3D"default" style=3D"margin-l=
eft:40px;"><li><p class=3D"" style=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;">Fresh mushroom=
 ravioli with pistachio pesto (Sicily, Italy)</p></li><li><p class=3D"" sty=
le=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;">Steamed clams fresh from the fish market (Port=
ugal)</p></li><li><p class=3D"" style=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;">Sliced mark=
et tomatoes, cucumbers and/or peppers with a drizzle of olive oil - often w=
ith tuna (Spain)</p></li><li><p class=3D"" style=3D"white-space:pre-wrap;">=
Sandwiches with bakery bread, salami, cheeses, and veggies (France)</p></li=
></ul>
</div>




















